<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">
<taxonomicName LSID="4AFA0BB6-0AA1-54A1-A9F3-2C6877EBE447" authority="Mosely, 1934" authorityName="Mosely" authorityYear="1934" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Leucotrichia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leucotrichia melleopicta" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melleopicta">Leucotrichia melleopicta Mosely, 1934</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="425" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Leucotrichia melleopicta Mosely, 1934. Male genitalia: A segments VII-X, lateral B segments VIII-X, ventral C segments IX-X, dorsal D phallus, lateral E phallus dorsal. Modified from Harris and Armitage (2019)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77371.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713499" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="425" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mosely" authorityYear="1934" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Leucotrichia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leucotrichia melleopicta" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melleopicta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Leucotrichia melleopicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. mutica" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="mutica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">L. mutica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also recorded from Panama. These species possess an inferior appendage with a similar shape, and the dorsal sclerite of the phallus of both bears a dorsal sclerite with a distinct apical emargination. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mosely" authorityYear="1934" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Leucotrichia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leucotrichia melleopicta" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melleopicta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Leucotrichia melleopicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the elongate basal sclerite of the phallus and the poorly developed basal loop (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Leucotrichia melleopicta Mosely, 1934. Male genitalia: A segments VII-X, lateral B segments VIII-X, ventral C segments IX-X, dorsal D phallus, lateral E phallus dorsal. Modified from Harris and Armitage (2019)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77371.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713499" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">11E</figureCitation>
), and by the enlarged apex of the mesoventral process on segment VII (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Leucotrichia melleopicta Mosely, 1934. Male genitalia: A segments VII-X, lateral B segments VIII-X, ventral C segments IX-X, dorsal D phallus, lateral E phallus dorsal. Modified from Harris and Armitage (2019)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77371.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713499" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">11A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77371.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713499" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" start="Figure 11" startId="F11">
