<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="425" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Mexico, Panama, Venezuela.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="425" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">
In the paper 
<bibRefCitation author="Harris, SC" journalOrPublisher="Insecta Mundi" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" pagination="1 - 54" refId="B13" refString="Harris, SC, Armitage, BJ, 2019. The Trichoptera of Panama. X. The Quebrada Rambala Drainage, with description of 19 new species of microcaddisfies (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae). Insecta Mundi 0707: 1 - 54" title="The Trichoptera of Panama. X. The Quebrada Rambala Drainage, with description of 19 new species of microcaddisfies (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae)." volume="0707" year="2019">Harris and Armitage (2019)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="Leucotricha" lsidName="Leucotricha melleopicta" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="melleopicta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Leucotricha melleopicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was redrawn to compare with 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. mutica" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="mutica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">L. mutica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as both species were common throughout Panama. In 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.499.8360" author="Thomson, RE" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" pagination="1 - 100" refId="B30" refString="Thomson, RE, Holzenthal, RW, 2015. A revision of the Neotropical caddisfly genus Leucotrichia Mosely, 1934 (Hydroptilidae: Leucotrichiinae). ZooKeys 499: 1 - 100, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.499.8360" title="A revision of the Neotropical caddisfly genus Leucotrichia Mosely, 1934 (Hydroptilidae: Leucotrichiinae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.499.8360" volume="499" year="2015">Thomson and Holzenthal (2015)</bibRefCitation>
the drawings were prepared from material collected in Mexico and compared to that of Venezuela. There were no comparisons with specimens from Central America. The drawings of genitalic features in the two publications are very similar. However, in the material from Mexico there was a posterior cleft in the ventral arm of the subgenital plate, which was not observed in material from Panama. This is a small character to observe and it could be present but not seen with the arm slightly turned, or it could be absent. The phallus drawings are similar, but in Harris and Armitage the subapical rods are separate, while in Thomson &amp; Holzenthal they are fused. However, the rods are not fixed in position and there is some lateral movement. This is based on the large number of examined specimens from Panama. Likewise the phallic apical rods are fused basally in Harris and Armitage, while they are separate, but closely aligned in Thomson and Holzenthal. Both arrangements of the phallic rods were observed in the material from Panama.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
